{
  "texts": [
    "Suppose we have a Lipschitz map F: R d → R n. Then the map F: R d → R d+n; F (x) = (x, F (x)), is biLipschitz.",
    "Remarkably, the entire argument which we need to carry out is completely invariant under such modifications of functions (which we carry out in Lemma 5.9, where the first d variables correspond to the identity).",
    "Moreover, the quantitative estimates needed, which in the approach of Dymond et al [22] depend on the biLipschitz constants, can be made to only depend on the Lipschitz constants.The second instance where biLipschitzness appears is of qualitative nature.",
    "Let Q be a cube inside R d of side-length r > 0 and π, κ:Q → R d L-Lipschitz maps.",
    "Then | Q det Dπ - Q det Dκ| ≤ Cr d-1 ∥π -κ∥ ∞ L d-1.This is shown already by Burago and Kleiner [11] when π, κ are also homeomorphisms (equivalently injective) using a kind of topological argument."
  ]
}